{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":52875,"duration_api_ms":52834,"num_turns":10,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"9fbdafcc-dd97-4e99-9ef7-baebe762cacb","total_cost_usd":0.31074075,"usage":{"input_tokens":8,"cache_creation_input_tokens":24679,"cache_read_input_tokens":204814,"output_tokens":2162,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":24679,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":8,"outputTokens":2162,"cacheReadInputTokens":204814,"cacheCreationInputTokens":24679,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.31074075,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"The amendment identifies a real dedupe collision bug. The model change (lines 469-482) now permits distinct named runs to share a started_at timestamp, but BeadStarted events (service.rs:448-451) only include project_id in details. Since the journal deduplicates on (timestamp, event_type, bead_id, details), two starts at the same timestamp become indistinguishable and the second is silently dropped. Completion events already include run_id/plan_hash via completion_journal_details() — start events should do the same.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-20-c613acbd","decision":"accept","rationale":"Verified in code: completion_journal_details() (model.rs:333) already includes run_id and plan_hash, but record_bead_start (service.rs:448-451) only writes `project={project_id}`. The fs.rs dedupe key (timestamp, event_type, bead_id, details) cannot distinguish two BeadStarted events from different named runs sharing the same started_at. This is a genuine correctness bug introduced by the model relaxation at lines 469-482 that allows new named runs to proceed despite a prior finalized run at the same timestamp. The fix — widening BeadStarted details to include run identity — is consistent with how completion events already work and is necessary to maintain journal audit trail integrity."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"ccfd8a1b-238f-4ddf-b520-8204ad9d703d"}
